Below is a floor plan of the plane you are in. Familiarize yourself with the location of the
exits. Note particularly the exits nearest you. Study how they are opened and also the
protective position you should assume during an emergency landing. When leaving,
move to the exits immediately. Do not go back for coats, purses, or other personal items.
A WORD ABOUT YOUR SEAT BELT-Rough air (turbulence) at high altitudes,
although infrequent, can be severe. When the seat belt sign is lighted in-flight, please
comply with the sign to prevent possible injury. Seasoned air travelers usually leave their
seat belts fastened all the time and pull them up snug whenever the seat belt sign is lighted.
Occasionally, because of schedule patterns, DC-8 aircraft equipped with ocean
ditching equipment also operate within the continental United States.
